  "local_port": 46116,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the steps for registering a company in India?",
  "response": "Registering a company in India involves several steps and requires adherence to legal protocols set by the Ministry of Corporate Affairs (MCA). Here's a detailed guide on the procedure:\n\n1. **Get Director Identification Number (DIN)**: \n   - All directors of the company must apply for a DIN. This can be done by filing Form DIR-3 and providing a photograph, identity proof, address proof, and relevant fee.\n\n2. **Obtain Digital Signature Certificate (DSC)**:\n   - Since all filings are done online, you need a DSC for the signing of forms. Authorized agencies issue DSC, and the certificate must be obtained for the directors.\n\n3. **Reserve Unique Name**:\n   - Apply for the name approval through the MCA portal. Two options are available: Reserve Unique Name (RUN) form or SPICe+ form. Ensure the name is unique and not similar to existing names or trademarks.\n\n4. **Prepare Documents**:\n   - Draft relevant documents like Memorandum of Association (MoA) and Articles of Association (AoA). MoA defines the company\u2019s scope of activities, and AoA sets rules and regulations for the management.\n\n5. **File Incorporation Forms**:\n   - File SPICe+ (Simplified Proforma for Incorporating a Company Electronically Plus) form via the MCA portal. Attach necessary documents such as:\n     - MoA\n     - AoA\n     - Identity and address proof of directors\n     - PAN card and passport photographs of directors\n     - Proof of office address\n     - NOC from the owner of the premises\n     - Declaration by directors and subscribers\n\n6. **PAN and TAN Application**:\n   - As part of SPICe+, you can also apply for PAN (Permanent Account Number) and TAN (Tax Deduction and Collection Account Number) for the company.\n\n7. **Payment of Fees**:\n   - Pay the registration and stamp duty fees through the MCA portal. The fees vary based on authorized capital and state of incorporation.\n\n8. **Verification and Approval**:\n   - The Registrar of Companies (RoC) reviews submitted forms and documents. If all details are accurate and complete, the RoC approves the incorporation and issues the Certificate of Incorporation.\n\n9. **Post-Incorporation Compliance**:\n   - After receiving the Certificate of Incorporation, comply with post-incorporation procedures such as:\n     - Opening a bank account in the name of the company.\n     - Appointment of the auditor within 30 days.\n     - Issue and allotment of shares.\n     - Compliance with the various statutory requirements relevant to the company\u2019s operations.\n\nThroughout the process, it's advisable to consult with a legal professional or a company secretary who can guide you through the detailed requirements and ensure compliance with all legal aspects.",
